{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492506"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1085"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.1,0.4,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50817"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1085"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36058"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1838"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43831"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50817"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 45-year-old man presents with a two month history of increasing fatigue which has become quite debilitating in the recent days. He has had episodes of itching over the last two weeks. He denies any joint or muscle pain. He does not smoke and drinks three glasses of wine at weekends. He is not on any medications. The physical examination is unremarkable. Laboratory investigations show his haemoglobin, bilirubin, serum lipase and complete blood count all within normal limits but the serum alkaline phosphatase is elevated. Antimitochondrial antibody and rheumatoid factor are negative. Ultrasound shows evidence of abnormal bile ducts and an MR cholangiogram shows multifocal stricturing of the intra and extrahepatic bile ducts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApart from being treated for this condition he will be screened for any associated conditions for which he might be at risk.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions should he be screened for next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangiocarcinoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Inflammatory bowel disease","Colorectal cancer","Gallbladder carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has primary sclerosing cholangitis. This condition is characterised by inflammation, fibrosis and stricturing of the intrahepatic and/or extrahepatic biliary ducts. It is estimated that roughly 70% of patients with primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) have underlying \u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E (IBD), most frequently ulcerative colitis. IBD and PSC are closely associated disease entities that, when present in combination, create a phenotypically different summative disease referred to as PSC-IBD. Due to the frequency of IBD in patients with PSC and the impact of IBD diagnosis on subsequent management including further surveillance, a colonoscopy to assess for IBD should be the priority investigation for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the patient is diagnosed with IBD, he would be recommended to undergo annual surveillance colonoscopy due to an increased risk of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst less common, the more sinister risk is that of\u003Cstrong\u003E cholangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Although screening practices vary, PSC patients generally undergo 6-12 month biliary imaging for this disease. This patient has already had detailed imaging of the biliary tree which has defined the changes of PSC without any concerning signs of malignancy, and no further investigation for cholangiocarcinoma is currently required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther complications associated with PSC include fat-soluble vitamin deficiencies (A, D, E, and K), metabolic bone disease, biliary strictures, cholangitis and cholelithiasis. These patients are also at increased risk of various cancers and in addition to those already mentioned, include \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, which can be evaluated through gallbladder and biliary imaging already described, and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which should be screened for in patients who develop cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["PSC patients should be screened for IBD at the time of initial diagnosis."],"references":["Gleeson D, Walmsley M, Trivedi PJ, et al. Surveillance for cholangiocarcinoma in patients with primary sclerosing cholangitis: Can we be more proactive? Frontline Gastroenterology 2023; 14:162\u201366.","Mertz A, Nguyen NA, Konsanos KH, et al. Primary sclerosing cholangitis and inflammatory bowel disease comorbidity: an update of the evidence. Annals of Gastroenterology 2019; 32:124-33.","Fausa O, Schrumpf E, Elgjo K. Relationship of inflammatory bowel disease and primary sclerosing cholangitis. Semin Liver Dis 1991; 11:31.","European Association for the Study of the Liver (2022). EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines on sclerosing cholangitis. Journal of hepatology, 77(3), 761\u2013806. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jhep.2022.05.011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36058"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36058"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-17T20:48:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-17T20:51:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1085"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50817"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1838"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Primary sclerosing cholangitis","synonyms":[